In an engineering bay that smelled faintly of solder and inevitability, an old programmer sat with a young one.

"You’re trying to store everything," the old one said.

"Yes," the young one replied. "I don’t want to lose anything."

The old one laughed--not unkindly.

"You will."

He drew a circle.

"This," he said, "is your memory."

A line moved around it.

"New data comes in. Old data leaves."

"That’s loss," the young one said.

"That’s life," the old one corrected.

He pointed to the circle.

"The system doesn’t break because it forgets."

He paused.

"It breaks because it refuses to."

